VALUES
(20, 4, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'The way of the wicked is as darkness:', 0, 37, 'question', 'Understanding the Path', 'What does the metaphor of darkness reveal about the nature of wickedness and its impact on one''s life choices? How can recognizing our own ''darkness'' lead to a more profound pursuit of wisdom and righteousness?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'attend to my words', 8, 26, 'connection', 'Listening to Wisdom', 'This phrase echoes the exhortation found in James 1:19, which instructs believers to be ''quick to hear, slow to speak, slow to anger.'' Both passages emphasize the importance of actively listening and engaging with wise counsel, suggesting that attentiveness to God''s words is foundational for spiritual growth and moral clarity.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 1:19", "description": "Encourages active listening and patience in communication."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'incline thine ear', 28, 45, 'theology', 'Posture of Reception', 'The phrase ''incline thine ear'' suggests a posture of humility and readiness to receive instruction. Many scholars believe this reflects a broader biblical theme of seeking wisdom and understanding, as seen in Proverbs 2:2, where one is encouraged to ''make your ear attentive to wisdom.'' This highlights the necessity of actively pursuing spiritual truth rather than passively awaiting it.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Proverbs 2:2", "description": "Discusses the active pursuit of wisdom."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'my sayings', 51, 61, 'greek', 'Significance of ''Sayings''', 'ρήμα (rhema, G4487) - saying, utterance. This term often refers to specific spoken words or messages, highlighting the importance of both the content and the context of God''s communication. Understanding this term emphasizes that the teachings being conveyed are not merely suggestions, but authoritative words to be heeded.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G4487", "description": "Identifies the Greek term for sayings."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'My son', 0, 6, 'question', 'Personal Relationship', 'What does it mean for God to address us as ''My son''? How does understanding this relationship shape our response to His words and teachings? Reflecting on this can deepen our appreciation for the personal nature of God''s guidance and the love behind His instruction.', 'heart.text.square', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'Let them not depart from thine eyes;', 0, 36, 'connection', 'Visual Remembrance', 'This phrase resonates with Deuteronomy 6:6-8, where the commands of God are to be ''on your hearts'' and ''bind them as a sign on your hands.'' The emphasis on keeping God''s words in sight and in heart highlights the importance of continual meditation and remembrance in daily life, fostering a deep, personal relationship with God.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Deuteronomy 6:6-8", "description": "Instructions for keeping God''s commandments central in life."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'keep them in the midst of thine heart.', 37, 75, 'theology', 'Heart as the Center', 'The heart in biblical theology represents the core of a person''s being, encompassing thoughts, emotions, and will. Many scholars believe this underscores the necessity of internalizing God''s wisdom, suggesting that true understanding and transformation come from allowing His teachings to permeate one''s innermost being (Proverbs 3:5-6).', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'Let them not depart from thine eyes;', 0, 36, 'question', 'Focus and Distraction', 'In what ways do distractions in your life pull your eyes away from God''s teachings? Consider practical steps to refocus your attention on His wisdom and guidance.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'keep them in the midst of thine heart.', 37, 75, 'greek', 'Heart in Greek', 'καρδία (kardia, G2588) - heart, inner self, center of thought and emotion. This term emphasizes the holistic nature of one''s being and the importance of internalizing wisdom.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G2588", "description": "Strong''s number for ''heart'' in the New Testament."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'For they are life unto those that find them, and health to all their flesh.', 0, 75, 'connection', 'Life and Health', 'This verse connects closely with John 6:63, where Jesus states, ''The words that I speak unto you, they are spirit, and they are life.'' Both passages emphasize the life-giving power of divine words. Furthermore, Proverbs 3:8 states that wisdom brings health to the body, reinforcing the idea that following God''s words leads to holistic well-being. These connections highlight the integral relationship between divine instruction and physical and spiritual vitality.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "John 6:63", "description": "Jesus speaks about the life-giving nature of His words."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 3:8", "description": "Wisdom is linked to health and well-being."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'For they are life unto those that find them, and health to all their flesh.', 0, 75, 'greek', 'Key Terms', 'The term ''health'' in the original Hebrew is רְפָא (rāpâ, H7495) - to heal, restore, or cure. This emphasizes not just physical health but also spiritual restoration that comes from adhering to God''s wisdom. The implication is a holistic healing that encompasses body, mind, and spirit, resonating with the overall theme of Proverbs concerning the value of wisdom.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7495", "description": "Strong''s number for \u05e8\u05b0\u05e4\u05b8\u05d0, relating to healing."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'For they are life unto those that find them, and health to all their flesh.', 0, 75, 'theology', 'Holistic Well-being', 'This verse suggests a theological perspective where God''s words are not only a source of spiritual enlightenment but also a means of physical and emotional health. Many scholars believe that this reflects the holistic nature of salvation—where spiritual truth leads to physical and emotional restoration, aligning with the broader Christian doctrine of shalom, or peace, which encompasses wholeness in all aspects of life.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the comprehensive nature of health through divine wisdom."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'For they are life unto those that find them, and health to all their flesh.', 0, 75, 'question', 'Finding Life', 'What does it mean to ''find'' the words of wisdom? How can actively seeking God''s truth in Scripture lead to both spiritual vitality and physical health in your daily life? Reflect on practical steps to incorporate this pursuit into your routine and how it affects your overall well-being.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'Keep thy heart with all diligence;', 0, 34, 'theology', 'Guarding the Heart', 'This verse emphasizes the importance of the heart in biblical theology, often seen as the center of moral and spiritual life. Many scholars believe that ''keeping the heart'' involves actively maintaining one’s values, emotions, and thoughts in alignment with God''s will. This concept is consistent with teachings found in Jeremiah 17:9, which warns about the deceitfulness of the heart, highlighting the need for vigilance in spiritual matters.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Jeremiah 17:9", "description": "This verse warns of the heart''s deceitfulness, reinforcing the need to guard it diligently."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'for out of it are the issues of life.', 35, 72, 'connection', 'Life''s Source', 'The phrase ''issues of life'' connects deeply with Matthew 12:34, where Jesus states, ''For out of the abundance of the heart the mouth speaks.'' This connection highlights that the heart is not just a passive organ but the source of one’s actions and words. Understanding the heart''s role as the wellspring of life encourages believers to cultivate purity and righteousness in their inner being.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 12:34", "description": "Jesus emphasizes the heart''s influence on speech and actions."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'Keep thy heart with all diligence;', 0, 34, 'greek', 'Heart in Greek', 'καρδία (kardia, G2588) - heart, the center of one''s being. This term signifies not just emotional aspects but also the will and intellect, suggesting a holistic view of the heart''s role in spiritual life. Understanding this Greek term helps clarify the depth of commitment required in ''keeping'' one''s heart.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G2588", "description": "The Greek word for heart, emphasizing its central role in life and faith."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'Keep thy heart with all diligence;', 0, 34, 'question', 'Heart''s Condition', 'What practices help you to diligently keep your heart aligned with God''s desires? Consider how daily choices and influences shape your spiritual state and reflect on specific actions you can take to guard your heart effectively.', 'heart.text.square', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'Put away from thee a froward mouth, and perverse lips put far from thee.', 0, 72, 'connection', 'Guarding Speech', 'This verse echoes the sentiment found in James 3:10, where it states, ''Out of the same mouth proceedeth blessing and cursing.'' The connection emphasizes the importance of our words and their capacity to affect both ourselves and others. By encouraging the removal of a froward mouth, Proverbs highlights the need for consistency and purity in speech, which aligns with the broader biblical teaching on the significance of our words.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 3:10", "description": "A related verse discussing the power of the tongue."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'froward mouth', 21, 34, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Froward''', 'The Hebrew term for ''froward'' is עִקְשָׁן (iqshan, H6141) - perverse, crooked, or twisted. This conveys a sense of speech that is not straightforward or honest. In the context of Proverbs, it warns against the dangers of deceitful communication, encouraging believers to speak truthfully and wisely.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H6141", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'perverse lips put far from thee.', 40, 72, 'theology', 'The Power of Words', 'Many scholars believe that this instruction reflects the biblical view of the power of words as seen throughout Scripture. The mouth is often seen as a reflection of the heart (Matthew 12:34). By urging the removal of perverse lips, Proverbs emphasizes the necessity of aligning one''s speech with righteousness, thereby fostering a life that is true and honorable before God.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 12:34", "description": "A verse illustrating the connection between heart and speech."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'Put away from thee a froward mouth, and perverse lips put far from thee.', 0, 72, 'question', 'Reflecting on Speech', 'In what ways do your words reflect the condition of your heart? How can you actively ''put away'' speech that is not honoring to God, and what practical steps can you take to cultivate a more truthful and uplifting dialogue in your daily interactions?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'Let thine eyes look right on,', 0, 29, 'connection', 'Focus on the Path', 'This phrase resonates with Philippians 3:14, where Paul urges believers to ''press toward the mark for the prize of the high calling of God in Christ Jesus.'' Both passages emphasize the importance of maintaining focus on one''s spiritual journey. Keeping one''s eyes fixed ahead is crucial to avoiding distractions that can lead one astray.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Philippians 3:14", "description": "Encouragement to focus on the spiritual goal."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'let thine eyelids look straight before thee.', 34, 78, 'theology', 'The Call to Discernment', 'This passage suggests that believers are called to a life of discernment, keeping their focus on the truth of God''s Word. Many scholars believe that a steadfast gaze on divine wisdom helps believers navigate moral ambiguities in life. This aligns with the theological notion that following God’s guidance leads to righteousness.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'Let thine eyes look right on,', 0, 29, 'greek', 'Greek Insight on ''Eyes''', 'ὀφθαλμός (ophthalmos, G3788) - eye, sight. This word emphasizes not just physical sight but spiritual perception. The call to look straight ahead implies a need for clarity and purpose in one’s spiritual vision.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G3788", "description": "Greek term for eye, highlighting spiritual awareness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'Let thine eyes look right on,', 0, 29, 'question', 'Personal Focus Reflection', 'What distractions in your life might hinder you from keeping your eyes focused on the path God has set before you? Reflecting on this can help identify areas where you need to realign your vision toward divine priorities.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'Ponder the path of thy feet,', 0, 28, 'connection', 'Cross-Reference to Psalm', 'Psalm 119:105 states, ''Thy word is a lamp unto my feet, and a light unto my path.'' This connection emphasizes the importance of divine guidance in determining the direction of our lives. Both passages highlight the need for careful consideration of our choices and actions, reinforcing the idea that wisdom comes from following God''s guidance.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 119:105", "description": "Similar theme of guidance and the importance of the right path."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'let all thy ways be established.', 33, 65, 'theology', 'Establishment of Ways', 'This passage suggests that establishing one''s ways is connected to a life of integrity and righteousness. Many scholars believe this reflects the biblical teaching that a life aligned with God''s principles leads to stability and success (Proverbs 3:5-6). The assurance of God directing our paths when we seek Him is foundational to Christian living.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Proverbs 3:5-6", "description": "Discusses trusting in the Lord for guidance."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'Ponder the path of thy feet,', 0, 28, 'question', 'Reflecting on Our Path', 'What specific actions or decisions in your life require deeper reflection to ensure they align with God''s will? How can you actively seek His guidance in these areas?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'Turn not to the right hand nor to the left:', 0, 43, 'connection', 'Guidance in Life''s Choices', 'This phrase echoes the command found in Deuteronomy 5:32, where the Israelites are instructed to observe the commandments without deviating. The connection emphasizes the importance of steadfastness in following God''s way, reinforcing the idea that straying from His path leads to spiritual danger. It invites readers to consider how they navigate life''s decisions.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Deuteronomy 5:32", "description": "This verse highlights the importance of obedience and not deviating from God''s commands."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'remove thy foot from evil.', 44, 70, 'theology', 'The Call to Holiness', 'This directive aligns with the Christian doctrine of sanctification, which emphasizes the believer''s need to turn away from sin and pursue holiness. Many scholars believe this reflects the transformative aspect of faith, where one is called to actively reject evil influences in their life, showing that faith is not merely a belief but an active pursuit of righteousness.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'Turn not to the right hand nor to the left:', 0, 43, 'question', 'Navigating Moral Choices', 'In what areas of your life are you tempted to deviate from God''s path? How can you ensure that your decisions align with His will, avoiding distractions that lead you away from righteousness?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'remove thy foot from evil.', 44, 70, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Evil''', 'רָע (ra, H7451) - evil, wickedness, harm. This Hebrew term encompasses not just moral evil but also the idea of calamity or distress. Understanding this broad definition can deepen one''s awareness of the various forms of evil one must avoid in life, which can include not only sinful acts but also harmful situations.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7451", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term for evil."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'attend unto my wisdom', 8, 29, 'connection', 'Wisdom in Proverbs', 'This phrase echoes Proverbs 4:7, where wisdom is described as the principal thing. Both verses emphasize the importance of seeking wisdom earnestly. Understanding this connection highlights the foundational role of wisdom in living a righteous life, serving as a guide through challenges.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 4:7", "description": "Wisdom as the principal thing"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'bow thine ear to my understanding', 35, 68, 'question', 'Listening for Understanding', 'What does it mean to ''bow thine ear'' to understanding? In what ways can we actively listen for wisdom in our daily lives? This invites reflection on our posture toward learning and the sources of wisdom we choose to engage with.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'attend unto my wisdom', 8, 29, 'theology', 'The Call to Wisdom', 'This verse illustrates the theological concept of divine wisdom being accessible to believers. Many scholars believe that this call reflects God''s desire for humans to seek understanding and live in accordance with His principles, fostering a relationship built on trust and obedience.', 'figure.mind.and.body', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Insights on the pursuit of wisdom"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'My son', 0, 6, 'greek', 'Familial Instruction', '''My son'' in Hebrew (בני, beni, H1121) - son, child. This term indicates a personal and intimate relationship, suggesting that the wisdom shared is not only for general guidance but is a heartfelt instruction from a parent to a child, emphasizing the importance of familial bonds in moral teaching.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1121", "description": "Strong''s number for ''son''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'That thou mayest regard discretion,', 0, 35, 'connection', 'Discretion in Scripture', 'This phrase connects with Proverbs 2:11, which states, ''Discretion will protect you, and understanding will guard you.'' Both verses emphasize the importance of discretion as a protective virtue in life. The relationship highlights how wisdom and understanding work together to guide one''s choices and actions, safeguarding against folly.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 2:11", "description": "Highlights the protective nature of discretion."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'and that thy lips may keep knowledge.', 36, 73, 'theology', 'The Importance of Knowledge', 'This passage suggests that the retention of knowledge is essential for moral and spiritual integrity. Many scholars believe that the ''lips'' symbolize not just speech but also the outward expression of inner wisdom. This reflects the broader theological principle that knowledge, particularly of God''s truth, is vital for living a righteous life.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'That thou mayest regard discretion,', 0, 35, 'question', 'Understanding Discretion''s Role', 'What does it mean to truly ''regard discretion'' in the context of daily choices? How can this verse guide you in decision-making processes that honor God and promote wisdom?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'and that thy lips may keep knowledge.', 36, 73, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Knowledge''', 'ידע (yada, H3045) - to know, be aware of, perceive. This Hebrew term emphasizes an experiential knowledge that goes beyond mere information, suggesting a deep relationship with truth. The call to keep knowledge implies an active, ongoing engagement with wisdom.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3045", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term for knowledge."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'the lips of a strange woman', 4, 31, 'connection', 'Warning Against Temptation', 'This phrase connects to James 1:14-15, which discusses how temptation leads to sin and ultimately death. Both passages underline the peril of succumbing to alluring but destructive influences, emphasizing the importance of discernment and self-control. Understanding these connections can help one appreciate the seriousness of the warning against the ''strange woman.''', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 1:14-15", "description": "Explains the process of temptation leading to sin."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'drop as an honeycomb', 32, 52, 'theology', 'Deceptive Sweetness', 'This imagery suggests that while the allure of sin may seem sweet and pleasant, it ultimately leads to bitterness and regret. Many scholars believe this reflects the biblical theme that sin often appears attractive but has destructive consequences, aligning with warnings found throughout Scripture about the nature of temptation.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'smoother than oil', 71, 88, 'greek', 'Smoothness and Deception', 'χάρις (charis, G5485) - grace, favor, sweetness. This term often conveys the idea of something that is pleasing to the senses. Here, it highlights how the seductive words of the ''strange woman'' can be enticing and deceptively beautiful, masking the dangers they pose.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G5485", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term meaning grace or sweetness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'the lips of a strange woman', 4, 31, 'question', 'Recognizing Deceptive Influences', 'In what ways do we encounter ''strange women'' in our lives today? How can we cultivate discernment to recognize and resist temptations that are appealing but ultimately harmful?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'But her end is bitter as wormwood, sharp as a twoedged sword.', 0, 61, 'connection', 'Bitter Endings', 'The phrase ''bitter as wormwood'' is echoed in Lamentations 3:15, where it speaks of experiencing bitterness and suffering. This connection emphasizes the destructive consequences of following the temptations represented by the ''strange woman.'' Proverbs 23:32 also reflects this idea, warning that the end of intoxicating drink is like a serpent that bites. Together, these verses illustrate the serious outcomes of straying from wisdom.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Lamentations 3:15", "description": "Highlights the theme of bitterness in suffering."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 23:32", "description": "Warns of the dangers and consequences of temptation."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'sharp as a twoedged sword.', 35, 61, 'theology', 'Word of God as Sword', 'Many scholars believe that the ''two-edged sword'' metaphor suggests the dual nature of God''s word, which can bring both judgment and salvation (Hebrews 4:12). This passage in Proverbs warns against the deceptive allure of temptation, paralleling how God''s word can cut through falsehood to reveal truth. The imagery serves as a reminder of the seriousness of moral choices and their ultimate consequences.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Hebrews 4:12", "description": "Illustrates the power of God''s word."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'But her end is bitter as wormwood,', 0, 34, 'question', 'Consequences of Choices', 'What does the comparison of her end to ''wormwood'' reveal about the ultimate consequences of succumbing to temptation? Reflecting on this metaphor, how can we apply this understanding to our own lives to avoid paths that lead to bitterness and regret?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'Her feet go down to death;', 0, 26, 'connection', 'Path to Destruction', 'This phrase connects with Romans 6:23, which states, ''For the wages of sin is death; but the gift of God is eternal life through Jesus Christ our Lord.'' Here, both verses emphasize the dire consequences of straying from wisdom and following sinful paths, illustrating a common biblical theme of life versus death.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Romans 6:23", "description": "Highlights the consequence of sin"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'her steps take hold on hell.', 27, 55, 'theology', 'Consequences of Sin', 'This passage suggests that engaging with temptation leads not only to physical death but to spiritual separation from God, often interpreted as ''hell.'' Many scholars believe this reflects the broader biblical teaching on the ultimate fate of those who reject divine wisdom and pursue destructive paths.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'Her feet go down to death;', 0, 26, 'question', 'Reflecting on Choices', 'What does it mean for our daily choices if some paths lead to death? How does this understanding influence the way we approach temptation and moral decisions in our lives?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');